"# Appendix B — Compressed 20,000-year timeline

Read this as a walking tour. One line per epoch. Each line names a
thing that mattered.

## Prehistory

- **~43,000 BC** — Lebombo bone (29 notches on baboon fibula, found in
  Border Cave, southern Africa). Possible lunar counting.
- **~18,000 BC** — Ishango bone (notched baboon fibula, found near
  headwaters of the Nile). Numerical patterns; interpretation debated.
- **~30,000–20,000 BC** — Other tally sticks appear across Europe and
  Africa.

## Ancient world

- **~3,000 BC** — Sumerian counting boards using tokens in grooves.
- **~2,700 BC** — Sumerian sexagesimal (base-60) number system in
  clay tablets. Still with us in minutes, seconds, and degrees.
- **~500 BC** — Chinese suan pan (abacus) formalised.
- **~150 BC** — Antikythera mechanism, Greek analogue astronomical
  calculator (discovered 1901 in a shipwreck; dated to about the 2nd
  century BC).
- **~200 BC – AD 200** — Roman abacus and Roman numerals in wide use.

## Middle Ages

- **~800** — Al-Khwarizmi (Persian mathematician) formalises algebra
  and introduces the Hindu-Arabic numeral system to the Islamic
  world. His name gives us the word *algorithm.*
- **~1200** — Fibonacci (Leonardo of Pisa) publishes *Liber Abaci*,
  introducing Hindu-Arabic numerals to Europe.
- **~1400** — Inca quipus (knotted-string records) in use across the
  Andes.

## Mechanical calculators

- **1614** — John Napier publishes logarithms.
- **1622** — William Oughtred invents the slide rule.
- **1642** — Blaise Pascal builds the Pascaline, a mechanical adder.
- **1673** — Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz builds the Step Reckoner, a
  mechanical calculator that could multiply.
- **1801** — Joseph-Marie Jacquard's loom, controlled by punched
  cards. First programmable machine.

## Electricity

- **1799** — Alessandro Volta invents the voltaic pile (first battery).
- **1820** — Hans Christian Ørsted discovers that electric current
  produces a magnetic field.
- **1827** — Georg Ohm publishes Ohm's law.
- **1831** — Michael Faraday demonstrates electromagnetic induction.
- **1837** — Cooke and Wheatstone patent the first practical
  electrical telegraph in Britain.
- **1844** — Samuel Morse sends the first US telegraph message from
  Washington to Baltimore.

## The 19th century — the analytical engine

- **1822–1837** — Charles Babbage designs the Difference Engine and
  then the Analytical Engine (never fully built in his lifetime).
- **1843** — Ada Lovelace publishes the notes on the Analytical Engine
  including what is widely considered the first algorithm intended
  for a machine.
- **1854** — George Boole publishes *An Investigation of the Laws of
  Thought.* Boolean algebra.

## Early 20th century — theory and tubes

- **1904** — John Ambrose Fleming patents the vacuum tube diode.
- **1906** — Lee de Forest patents the triode (amplifying vacuum tube).
- **1928** — Vannevar Bush builds the differential analyzer, a
  mechanical analog computer, at MIT.
- **1936** — Alan Turing publishes *On Computable Numbers*,
  introducing the Turing machine and proving the halting problem.
- **1937** — Claude Shannon's MIT master's thesis, *A Symbolic
  Analysis of Relay and Switching Circuits*, maps Boolean algebra to
  circuits.
- **1937** — George Stibitz at Bell Labs builds Model K, a binary
  adder from relays.
- **1938** — Konrad Zuse in Berlin starts building the Z1.
- **1941** — Zuse's Z3, the first working programmable digital
  computer (relay-based).

## World War II and after

- **1943** — Colossus, British code-breaking machine at Bletchley Park.
  Used vacuum tubes.
- **1945** — John von Neumann drafts the *First Draft of a Report on
  the EDVAC*, describing the stored-program architecture.
- **1946** — ENIAC (Presper Eckert and John Mauchly) at the University
  of Pennsylvania. ~17,468 vacuum tubes.
- **1947** — Bardeen, Brattain, and Shockley at Bell Labs invent the
  transistor.
- **1947** — Grace Hopper documents the first computer 'bug' (an
  actual moth) in the Harvard Mark II log.
- **1949** — EDSAC at Cambridge (Maurice Wilkes) runs its first
  program. First practical stored-program computer.

## The 1950s — high-level languages

- **1951** — UNIVAC I delivered to the US Census Bureau.
- **1954** — IBM begins developing FORTRAN.
- **1957** — FORTRAN compiler released.
- **1958** — Jack Kilby at Texas Instruments builds the first
  integrated circuit.
- **1959** — Robert Noyce at Fairchild files for a patent on a planar
  IC in silicon.
- **1958–1959** — John McCarthy at MIT invents Lisp.
- **1959** — COBOL specified.
- **1959** — DEC PDP-1.

## The 1960s — networks and interactive computing

- **1961** — Fernando Corbato at MIT demonstrates the first
  time-sharing system, CTSS.
- **1963** — ASCII standard published.
- **1964** — IBM System/360, the first family of compatible computers.
- **1964** — Dartmouth BASIC (John Kemeny, Thomas Kurtz).
- **1965** — Gordon Moore's article predicting exponential growth in
  IC transistor count — later dubbed Moore's law.
- **1967** — Simula 67 introduces object-oriented programming ideas.
- **1969** — Ken Thompson and Dennis Ritchie at Bell Labs write the
  first Unix.
- **1969** — ARPANET goes live between UCLA, SRI, UCSB, and Utah.

## The 1970s — the microprocessor

- **1971** — Intel 4004, the first commercial microprocessor.
  4-bit, ~2,300 transistors.
- **1972** — Dennis Ritchie writes C.
- **1972** — Intel 8008, 8-bit.
- **1973** — Vint Cerf and Bob Kahn publish the design of TCP.
- **1974** — Intel 8080, widely used in early microcomputers.
- **1975** — MOS 6502 designed by Chuck Peddle at MOS Technology, sold
  at $25.
- **1975** — Guy Steele and Gerald Sussman publish Scheme.
- **1975** — MITS Altair 8800, the first mass-market personal computer
  kit.
- **1976** — Apple I (Wozniak, Jobs).
- **1977** — Apple II, Commodore PET, TRS-80 all released. The
  personal computer arrives.
- **1978** — Texas Instruments Speak & Spell.
- **1978** — Motorola 68000.
- **1979** — VisiCalc, the first spreadsheet, on the Apple II.

## The 1980s — mass-market personal computing

- **1981** — IBM PC.
- **1982** — Commodore 64 released. Best-selling single computer
  model in history (~17 million units).
- **1983** — Richard Stallman announces GNU.
- **1983** — TCP/IP replaces NCP on ARPANET.
- **1984** — Apple Macintosh.
- **1985** — Commodore Amiga 1000.
- **1985** — Windows 1.0.
- **1985** — Abelson and Sussman publish *Structure and Interpretation
  of Computer Programs* (SICP).
- **1988** — Morris worm — the first large internet worm.
- **1989** — Tim Berners-Lee proposes the World Wide Web at CERN.

## The 1990s — the Web

- **1991** — Linus Torvalds releases Linux 0.01.
- **1991** — Berners-Lee's WWW code goes public.
- **1993** — NCSA Mosaic browser.
- **1993** — Charles Petzold publishes... wait no, that was 1999.
  1993 was *Windows Programming*. Sorry.
- **1994** — Netscape founded.
- **1995** — Java 1.0.
- **1995** — JavaScript (Brendan Eich, at Netscape).
- **1996** — DVD.
- **1997** — Deep Blue beats Kasparov.
- **1998** — Google founded.
- **1999** — Charles Petzold publishes *Code: The Hidden Language of
  Computer Hardware and Software.*

## The 2000s — mobile and cloud

- **2001** — Wikipedia launches.
- **2004** — Facebook.
- **2004** — 64-bit x86 (AMD, then Intel).
- **2006** — AWS launches EC2 and S3. Cloud computing goes mainstream.
- **2007** — iPhone.
- **2008** — Android.
- **2009** — Bitcoin genesis block.

## The 2010s — deep learning

- **2012** — AlexNet wins ImageNet, kicking off the deep learning
  revolution.
- **2014** — GANs (Ian Goodfellow).
- **2016** — AlphaGo beats Lee Sedol.
- **2017** — Vaswani et al. publish *Attention Is All You Need.* The
  transformer.
- **2018** — GPT-1 (OpenAI); BERT (Google).
- **2019** — GPT-2.

## The 2020s — the LLM era

- **2020** — GPT-3.
- **2021** — Anthropic founded.
- **2022** — ChatGPT (November).
- **2023** — GPT-4; Claude 2; Gemini (from merged Google Brain +
  DeepMind); DeepSeek's first models.
- **2024** — Claude 3 family; Gemini 1.5; open-weights ecosystem
  expands (Llama, Mistral, Qwen, DeepSeek).
- **2025** — DeepSeek's efficient training methods draw industry
  attention. LLMs become widely embedded in developer tools.
- **2026** — Motoi Scheme released. Sixteen chapters of the Book of
  Code arrive at chapter 16.

## Reading the timeline

A few things jump out.

- The gap between the abacus and the first electric switch is about
  five thousand years. The gap between the transistor and the LLM is
  about seventy-five. The compound curve is real.
- Every generation stood on the previous one. Boole would not have
  been possible without Descartes and Newton. Shannon would not have
  been possible without Boole. Turing needed both. The transistor
  needed Faraday, Maxwell, and half a dozen other physicists. The
  LLM needs everything above it plus modern statistics.
- The people are mostly individuals, but the last thirty years are
  increasingly teams. Vaswani's transformer paper had eight authors.
  A modern LLM training run has hundreds of engineers behind it.

## Twenty thousand years, one thread

The bone remembers. The abacus remembers with position. Boole reasons
about the memory. Shannon makes the reasoning electric. The transistor
makes it small. The chip makes it dense. The CPU makes it programmable.
The network makes it social. The LLM makes it linguistic.

Every step was a person or a team, standing on the last step.

That is the thread. Follow it forward and see where it goes next.
")
